          "body": "The chapter opens with a scene of maximum military pressure: Nebuchadnezzar, all his army, and all the kingdoms of the earth are fighting against Jerusalem and its remaining cities (34:1). Into that crisis, God gives Jeremiah a specific, personal word for the king — not generalities, but named facts: Babylon will burn the city (34:2); Zedekiah will be captured and will see Nebuchadnezzar eye to eye and face to face (34:3); he will go to Babylon (34:3). The oracle is uncomfortably specific — it forecloses every hope of escape. Yet the *akh* of 34:4 ('yet hear the word of the LORD') opens a narrow mercy within the judgment: you will not die by the sword. You will die in peace. Spices will be burned at your burial; mourners will lament 'Alas, lord!' (34:5) — the honorable funeral rite of a legitimate king. The God of Jeremiah 34 is not a God of undifferentiated wrath. He distinguishes between the fate Zedekiah fears (violent death at the sword) and the fate Zedekiah will receive (exile, captivity, but an honorable death). The two things are held together: the judgment is real and the mercy is real. Jeremiah obeys immediately, speaking all these words to Zedekiah in Jerusalem while the battle still rages and only Lachish and Azekah remain standing (34:6-7)."
