          "body": "Verse 17 is the chapter's theological center, and one of the most rhetorically precise sentences in the entire book of Jeremiah: 'You have not obeyed Me in proclaiming release (*deror*) each man to his brother and each man to his neighbor. Behold, I am proclaiming a *deror* to you — to the sword, to the pestilence, and to the famine; and I will make you a terror to all the kingdoms of the earth.' The irony is not accidental or merely literary. It is legal. Judah proclaimed a *deror* under oath and revoked it; God now pronounces a *deror* that cannot be revoked. The word that should have named liberation now names the three instruments of covenant-curse — the same triad that appears across the entire Jeremianic corpus as the comprehensive signature of divine judgment. The precision of the counter-proclamation — they did not release their brothers from service to fellow humans, so God releases them into service to sword, pestilence, and famine — reflects the lex talionis logic of covenant law. What you withheld from your brothers, you will receive from My hand. The mercy you could have shown has closed; the mercy God once offered has been exhausted. 'I will make you a terror to all the kingdoms of the earth' (34:17) reverses the Abrahamic calling to be a blessing to all nations."
